This is the revised and expanded version of the story Anari, Maladwen, Creapiing, Selilya and myself all started writing long ago. To help explain chronology this happened during the time when the Harvest was infected with the Plague of Bertoxxulous, and it ends shortly after the Harvest destroyed the Drachnid Queen in the Crystal Caverns to cure themselves.<br>
<br>
There should be a little more to come soon as well, and I will add that in as we get it done.<br>
<br>
Hope you enjoy.<br>
<br>
~ Khasirath<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
Vengeance<br>
<br>
--------<br>
<br>
Anari<br>
<br>
There was no sun here, even in the forest beyond the cavernous entrance to the city. It was as if the sun - the embodiment of good and light - refused to show itself in the face of such perversion and deviance.  Thus was the life of the Teir`Dal, forever in the dark and the shadows.  Always shunned by the light. <br>
<br>
She had not tread the stone floors of Neriak in many years.  There had been no reason for her to return, no desire to revisit that part of her life.  Yet as she walked past the soldiers that guarded the entrance to the Third Gate, a strange sense of calm washed over her - a feeling that her life had finally come full circle. <br>
<br>
She ran an ebon hand through her platinum hair as she walked, her emerald eyes adjusting to the shifts in magical light with forgotten ease.  With a sigh, she brought her thoughts out of the past and back to the task at hand.  She had not returned to Neriak for a walk down memory lane, but to attain that which she had hungered for since the first moment she had met him. <br>
<br>
Vengeance. <br>
<br>
The Maiden’s Fancy was a house of free flowing alcohol and easy women - some Teir`Dal, some not.  It was the place to be if you wanted a good time, or information.  She knew that the one she sought would be here, partly for the wine and debauchery, but more for the loose tongues and purses of the patrons. <br>
<br>
She pushed the door open, rapidly taking in every face in the room.  A smile crossed her lips when she saw her prey.  In a few strides she was standing beside the young Teir`Dal woman.  She placed a hand on the young one’s shoulder, leaning in so her lips were close to the other’s ear. <br>
<br>
“Forgive the interruption, young S`Therik, but I have an urgent message from your brother Khasirath.”<br>
<br>
The young one turned her head, “Oh, what does he want of me now?” she said with a sly grin, her voice awash with sarcasm. <br>
<br>
“Again, forgive me, but this is not the place.” <br>
<br>
The young one narrowed her emerald eyes a moment, then nodded.  She rose from her seat and followed out into the streets.  In silence they moved to a secluded spot not far from the brothel. “What is this ‘urgent’ message?” <br>
<br>
Anari spun suddenly, her hand balling into a fist the instant before it connected with the young S`Therik’s jaw.  “Really now, Tzanntiel, has the Ebon Mask taught you nothing?”  Grabbing the surprised young woman by the hair she drove her face into the cavern wall.  “I’m quite disappointed.” <br>
<br>
Holding the stunned woman up against the wall, she slowly and methodically searched the young one's body, removing all the weapons she found.  When she was finished, she spun her around so they were eye to eye. <br>
<br>
Tzanntiel could see the hatred in the eyes of her assailant.  “Who are you?” she hissed in anger, ignoring the scrapes oozing blood down her cheek. <br>
<br>
Anari shook her head, striking out once again and slapping the woman hard.  “Questions, questions, questions.  You S`Therik’s and all your god damn questions!&quot;  She slammed her hand against the wall beside Tzanntiel’s head, bringing her face an inch from the woman’s.  “Tell me S`Therik whore child, do you honestly think I came here to answer your questions?” <br>
<br>
“Then what do you want?” Tzanntiel growled as her emerald eyes blazed with hate. <br>
<br>
Anari sneered, wrapping her hand around the woman’s throat.  “That was another question, but it is one I am more than willing to answer.” <br>
<br>
Her free hand moved quickly, removing the dirk from her belt and driving it into Tzanntiel’s stomach. “Your dear brother brutalized me.”<br>
<br>
She withdrew the dirk, only to stab her once again. “He humiliated me.” <br>
<br>
Another thrust of the blade.  “Hell he even killed me!” <br>
<br>
Closely she watched every grimace and silenced every cry of pain with a squeeze of her hand.  She did not flinch as the younger Rogue's nails tore into the flesh of her wrist.  With a wicked smile, she released her hold on the young one, letting her fall to the ground.  Already a pool of blood spread across the stones beneath them. <br>
<br>
She looked down at the rapidly paling Teir`Dal.  “Do you begin to understand child? You are going to be my message to him.”  She knelt down, uncaring of the blood staining the raven-scale of her leggings. <br>
<br>
“You will suffer, though not as I suffered, and you may yet survive this, if you are strong enough.”  She brushed the hair from the woman’s face and lifted a now cold hand into hers. <br>
<br>
“Are you strong enough?” <br>
<br>
In one fluid motion, she sliced her dirk across Tzanntiel’s exposed throat and placed the young woman’s hand over the wound. <br>
<br>
“If you wish to die, all you need to do is let go.  But to survive, that is up to you.  Either way, my message will be delivered.  He wanted me to hate, and so I do.” <br>
<br>
Without a second thought, she stood and walked away.  Without a moment of regret, she made her way out of the maze that was Neriak and into the Nektulos Forest.  She would not return, she knew, nothing could ever bring her back to that accursed place.  She had no need.  She carried the seed of the Teir`Dal now, the essence of what they were - what she now was.  She had been shown the power of hate, and had answered its call. <br>
<br>
As she stepped into the warmth of the sun that shone throughout the Commonlands, her bloodied hand reached toward her face and removed the mask that had created the illusion she had needed.  Her image shimmered, and then melted away to that of a Fier`Dal.  With a smile on her face, Anari Ravensblade headed back to Freeport. <br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Maladwen<br>
<br>
Applause was heard from behind Anari just as she entered the gates of the city of corruption.  She spun without a second thought, her dirk meeting the man's throat. <br>
<br>
“I'm a messenger from the General, Anari.  I was just applauding your show.  You have become everything he remembers, and more.” <br>
<br>
The young Elf gently removed the dirk from his neck and bowed before her.  She raised a brow at him, having not been pleased that the General was watching her.  The Fier`Dal dressed in simple leather removed something from his shirt.  It was a red box in the shape of a heart.  He handed it to her, and it said something in a tongue she couldn't seem to make out.  “It means, ‘To be Happy on a Such a Joyous Occasion’,” the elf said before disappearing into the shadows. <br>
<br>
--------<br>
<br>
Tzanntiel<br>
<br>
Tzanntiel struggled to her feet, pressing her back against the rough wall for support.  She held one arm pressed over the wounds on her stomach as she tightly clenched her slashed throat with the other hand.  She could feel her whole body trembling and growing colder, her fingers slick with her own life's blood, making it hard to keep her grip. <br>
<br>
She panted raggedly as she tried to focus her vision on the alley ahead of her, foamy blood flecking her lips.  Weakly she staggered down the alley, her legs so cold and weak she feared she would collapse at each step. <br>
<br>
The shifting glow of Neriak's lights dazzled her clouding eyes, confusing her as she limped down the street, growing numb to the desperate pain.  Faces swam through her vision as she stumbled, their eyes turning away in disgust.  In Neriak, no one would help the weak unless they had a vested interest, and usually common blood.  Tzanntiel's pale lips moved silently as she prayed that she might find a House servant out on some business.<br>
<br>
At first her mind was only filled with fear and blind panic.  She knew her House had enemies, but S`Therik's strength had protected her from such overt attacks before.  And this stranger's words had led her to other thoughts; she could not have been Teir`Dal if Khasirath had done those things to her.  Unless she had been a Heretic, Tzann thought.  But the pain made it hard for her to focus on any one thought, her mind jumping from fear to fear, panic stealing her already labored breath. <br>
<br>
She staggered this way and that, trying to find her way to the Lodge of the Dead, which was near the manse of House S`Therik.  But all the streets looked the same, and her weakening heart pounded harder as she thought she surely must be lost.  Darkness closed in tighter as she realized she'd turned into a dead-end alley.  Tears streaming down her cold cheeks, she leaned against the wall to try to catch her bearings. <br>
<br>
In a swoon she closed her eyes, her mind tumbling deeper into the pain as it razed through every nerve of her being.  The fear began to burn away as her anger grew - anger at her own confusion and weakness, anger at the pain itself.  And above all blazed an intense hatred for the woman that had brought it all upon her.  Tzanntiel gasped softly, fresh blood bubbling past her lips as the hatred swelled to permeate her entire being.  For the first time in her life she understood with unmistakable clarity the rapturous snarl she had seen on her father's and brother's faces in battle.  For the first time, the Father's own Hatred touched the girl, and she understood what she had only been paying service to in words for so many years. <br>
<br>
Opening her emerald eyes, Tzanntiel stared at the alley's end, and for a moment the fear almost returned as she thought perhaps she had never left the alley she'd been attacked in.  Perhaps everything she'd seen had just been a confused dream.<br>
<br>
-----------<br>
<br>
Selilya<br>
<br>
The meeting of the Triad had ended well, and Selilya had donned her cloak and was walking back to her cottage.  She nodded at the skeletal servant of House S`Therik as she stepped onto the pathway.  It saluted, holding the gate open for her and her guard to pass. <br>
<br>
The Triad had discussed many issues this night, and Selilya was mulling over the main topics yet again.  The threat of war was very real and training was a concern.  She was thinking of several options, when she heard a loud crash in the alley she was approaching.  Gathering her wits she drew her dagger, then peered into the darkness.  Corporal P`Traz stepped in front of her to ensure her safety and drew his sword.  Selilya could see someone nearby, struggling to stand… <br>
<br>
“What in the name of Innoruuk…” Selilya gasped.  As she and the Corporal approached, the silhouette stumbled to Selilya's feet.  She bent down to turn the female shadow over.  “Tzanntiel! No, no… you hold on,” she whispered to Khasirath's sister. <br>
<br>
“Corporal P`Traz!” she yelled out to her assigned protector.  “Quickly! Give me your cloak, so we can cover this child.  Good.  Now, go get the Thresher and his sister, the Cleric.”  She placed the cloak on the pale, shivering Tzanntiel.  There was so much blood caked on her that Selilya could not imagine how she lived. <br>
<br>
“Don't die on us.  Hang on.  Your brother and sister are coming,” Selilya softly spoke.  “I promise…we'll find the one who did this.  They will pay dearly…very dearly.” <br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
Maladwen<br>
<br>
Maladwen smirked at this sight, and left the gates of Neriak unnoticed as usual.  He liked the fact that Anari had done this, chosen such a cruel way to set an example, something he'd done many times in the past.  He left the city with little confrontation. <br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
Anari<br>
<br>
The sun had begun its descent behind the dunes of sand.  Night was fast approaching and the skiff would be arriving soon.  Ignoring the prattle of the gnome that stood before the dock, Anari dipped her wounded hand into the ocean water.  A hiss of pain escaped her lips as the salt water coursed into the open gashes on her wrist, washing the blood away. <br>
<br>
The brat had hurt her more than she had thought.  She could see the tendons beneath her skin move every time she shifted her fingers, the flesh having been torn away.  Leaving her injured hand in the water she reached into her pack and retrieved a roll of bandages.  Not waiting for her hand to dry she began to wrap her wrist. <br>
<br>
A smile crossed her face.  She had done it.  She had beaten the bastard at his own game.  True, he probably wouldn’t morn the loss of his sister should Tzanntiel die, but she had entered his domain and had attacked one close to him.  There would be retribution, of that she was certain, but it would take him some time to narrow down the number of people who hated him. <br>
<br>
The hairs on the back of her neck stood on end a heartbeat before she heard the footsteps on the dock.  Her heart all but stopped at the thought that Khasirath had found her already.  As the shadow of the person blocked the setting sun she instinctively reached for her dirk.  Turning her head she looked up, her eyes going wide in recognition.  “General?  You were the last person I was expecting.” <br>
<br>
A small smirk formed on Maladwen Shadowlurker’s lips, like a child with a secret.  “I’m full of surprises.  Mind if I sit beside you?” <br>
<br>
“Please do.”  She nodded and went back to her bandaging. <br>
<br>
He watched her as he sat, his feet dangling over the side of the dock.  “What happened?” <br>
<br>
She chuckled as she tied off the ends of the bandage with her teeth and free hand.  “Come now, General, no games.  I spoke to your messenger and know that you have been watching me.” <br>
<br>
“Aye, that I have.  That was quite a show you put on for me back in Neriak.  What was that all about Anari?  I've rarely seen you act with such… ferocity.” <br>
<br>
She slipped her hand back into her scaled glove, an uncommon hatred glowing in her eyes.  “A little payback is all, and it wasn’t for you.  It was something that’s been coming for a long time.” <br>
<br>
He raised a brow, noticing the look in her eyes.  “He must have done something awful.” <br>
<br>
She shook her head.  “No, it wasn’t awful. It was worse than that.”  She turned to face him.  “Why should you care?  Last time we spoke you made it perfectly clear that you wanted nothing to do with me.  Why the change?” <br>
<br>
“I feel it is time to renew friendships.  Anari, you still have a strong place in my heart.  I was angered, and I felt betrayed, two things that don't mix easily with me.  But I'm sure you're happy now, you have someone you care about...  The only thing I see wrong is that you have the need to take revenge on someone.” <br>
<br>
Anari stared at him, astonished.  “Happy?”  She chuckled.  “My life is anything but happy, General.  And as for that someone you mentioned - he was a mistake.  Hurting you was a mistake.” <br>
<br>
He looked at her sadly.  “Anari, I…”<br>
<br>
The blabbering gnome talking about how the ship was coming interrupted him.  He got to his feet, offering her his hand to help her up. <br>
<br>
She took his hand in hers and rose.  He pulled her onto the skiff, only to catch her as her foot slipped on the wet wood and she fell into his arms.  She swallowed the lump that suddenly formed in her throat.  “Are you going to Velious, General?” <br>
<br>
He smiled at her.  “Aye, I am.” <br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Khasirath<br>
<br>
Khasirath pounded down the streets of Neriak, four House soldiers following behind with the young Priestess Vhalshae in their midst.  The Thresher's eyes blazed with deadly fury, and most who saw him coming stepped quickly out of his way.  Any who did not were roughly shouldered aside.  He did not slow a bit until he came to the place where the Winnower knelt beside a prone figure draped in a bloody cloak.  His escort had fallen behind, unable to match his breakneck speed or his intimate knowledge of the twisting passages of the Third Gate. <br>
<br>
Khasirath dropped heavily to his knees beside the Winnower, his face paling as he looked at his sister's horrible wounds.  “Innoruuk, let her survive this,” he muttered as he pulled off his gauntlets to cup her cold cheek in his palm, trying to rouse her.  “Tzann, I'm here.  Vhalshae is too.  It's alright now, I will not let you go.” <br>
<br>
Tzanntiel's eyes fluttered open a moment, her pale lips moving without sound.  Khasirath couldn't even tell is she could see him.  He saw her trembling hand clutched at her throat, the blood sluggishly oozing from between her fingers.  He laid his hand over hers, helping her hold the wound as he reached deep within his own hatred. <br>
<br>
&quot;My life to yours, sister,&quot; he whispered as he let his own life force and hate flow into her, and the hideous slash began to close. <br>
<br>
Vhalshae had reached them at last, and she knelt across from Khasirath, taking Tzanntiel's free hand into her own.  Softly she began to chant in prayer, and her own powers began to strengthen Tzanntiel, healing her other wounds. <br>
<br>
Selilya continued to stroke the young Rogue's hair as Khasirath and Vhalshae poured their power and life into their sister.  The worry faded from the Winnower's brow as the color returned to Tzanntiel's cheeks and her eyes opened, clearly focusing on her brother's face. <br>
<br>
“Khas,” she whispered, her voice weak, but full of relief. <br>
<br>
“Who did this to you?” he asked, stroking her cheek gently with his fingers. <br>
<br>
Tzanntiel frowned, still struggling with the pain and the powerful hate she felt, “I don't know... she did not tell me her name.  She said it was a message to you.  She said you had brutalized her and humiliated her and killed her.  She was a Rogue; I recognized her Ravenscale armour.  And she looked Teir`Dal.  But you would not do those things to one of our people, would you?”  Her eyes searched her brother's face in confusion. <br>
<br>
Khasirath growled deeply as it all came clear.  “Ravensblade,” he said.  “She is not Teir`Dal, Tzann.  She is Fier`Dal, and she will pay in blood for what she has done to you, I swear it.” <br>
<br>
Tzanntiel nodded a little, trying to sit up.  She gasped in pain, and Khasirath gently pushed her back down.  For once she did not fight him, and she gave Vhalshae's hand a gentle squeeze of thanks.  The young Priestess looked drained from drawing so much of herself into the healing. <br>
<br>
Khasirath looked up at Selilya, “Thank you for helping my sister, Winnower.  I owe you a great deal for that.” <br>
<br>
Selilya smiled, waving a hand dismissively,  “We of the Harvest are family as surely as you S`Therik's are family.  You do not owe me anything.” <br>
<br>
Khasirath bowed his head in thanks, a thin smile on his lips, though Selilya could see the dangerous rage burning in his violet eyes. <br>
<br>
“And Thresher, if you need any help with this Ravensblade, you need only call upon the Harvest.  The enemy of one is the enemy of us all,” she added. <br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded, though he looked reluctant.  “Thank you Winnower.  I need only find her, and then I will end it myself.  This matter has become very personal.” <br>
<br>
Selilya nodded in understanding. <br>
<br>
Khasirath gathered his gauntlets up and tucked them under his belt, then scooped Tzanntiel up carefully to carry her home.  Vhalshae walked behind him, slipping her hands into the sleeves of her robes.  Silently the four soldiers fell into step around them. <br>
<br>
Over his shoulder Khasirath said, “I will have the cloak cleaned and returned to you on the morrow.  Thank you again, Winnower.” <br>
<br>
