Creapiing followed his gaze a moment, then looked back at him with a smile, “I must say Khasirath, I have not been without my slave Kurmudgin tasting my food for so long that I can't remember when I have not gotten cold, half-eaten portions for my dinner.  To have you here, cooking for me, I shall grow weak and complacent.  Another good reason to finish this quickly.”  She laid a carefully tied fly next to the last one.<br>
<br>
He grinned back at her, shaking his head, “Weak and complacent?  I cannot picture it.  Though I am very glad you've been enjoying my cooking.  It is simple fare, but I try to make it flavorful.”  He picked up another bit of bat fur, trying to pin it onto the hook long enough to get the thread bound around it.<br>
<br>
“Khasirath, try this.”  Creapiing reached over and gently rubbed more kobold fat onto his hand.  “Now knot it at the end just so, and you will catch the biggest fish this day.”<br>
<br>
He nodded and grinned at the warmth of her hand and the slickness of the grease.  The trick worked and he was able to finish the fly well enough to call it useable, though it was not to his eye anywhere near as well made as the Reaper's.  “Indeed, we shall see.  It's been some time since I've found time to fish.  Shamefully I've been buying fish in Oggok to make fish rolls for my travels.”<br>
<br>
“You should instruct your slaves to catch them for you.  Or have you kept them too busy with other duties?” she asked, looking at the Thresher inquiringly.<br>
<br>
He looked into her eyes, struck as always by the similarity in color to his own.  “They have many other duties that keep them busy.  And having them follow me around fishing would be a bother.  I have enough trouble getting some of my servants to leave me a moment's privacy.”<br>
<br>
She smiled slyly, “I am sure they rise to your satisfaction Khasirath.”  Motioning toward the poles she added, “Let us catch a fish.”<br>
<br>
He scooped up the poles, handing one to the Reaper before he fixed his new lure to the end of his line.  “Indeed they do, my Reaper.  The servants of S`Therik are very loyal and very well trained.  None has ever failed to meet my needs.”  He settled back down next to her, casting his line down through the ice into the darkness of the water.<br>
<br>
“Khasirath?” Creapiing said, her voice unusually soft, “Do they meet all of your needs?  Are your slaves and lovers enough for you?”<br>
<br>
He turned his head to again study her eyes, tilting his head just a bit in thought.  “They meet the immediate needs of the flesh, I imagine, my Reaper.  But I'll admit sometimes it seems not to be enough.  Perhaps I simply grow restless...” he let the thought trail off, unwilling to speak the rest aloud just yet.<br>
<br>
Creapiing laughed, “You have a fish on your line Thresher.  Best pull it in and break its neck quickly.”<br>
<br>
He felt his face flush as he realized his thoughts had wandered away with him.  With practiced efficiency he drew in the line and his struggling catch, hauling the sleek and darkly speckled salmon onto the ice away from the hole to grab it quickly, snapping its neck with both hands.<br>
<br>
Creapiing gasped at the size of the fish.  “Like I said, you would get the biggest fish!  Why is it that the worst flies catch the biggest fish?  Ugly flies and big fish, light and dark, love and hate -- the great mysterious connections of Innoruuk,” she mused aloud.<br>
<br>
Khasirath glanced back at her with a bemused smile as he pried the hook back out of the fish's lip.  “I never stopped to see the Father's Will in fishing, my Reaper.  But you make an interesting argument.”<br>
<br>
He drew a slim blade and quickly gutted and filleted the salmon, turning to his smoldering spit to pick out some cleaned bat wings he'd had warming there.  After adding some seasonings from a small pouch he wrapped the fillets and set the bundles over the fire to cook.<br>
<br>
As he tended to their dinner Creapiing spoke as she packed up the poles, “Thresher, I have never properly thanked you for saving my life on my last fishing trip.  Allow me to now.”  She picked out a very unique fishing fly and moved toward Khasirath as he stood up from his cooking.  Standing nearly his height, and looking into his eyes, she moved closer until a fine silk thread would barely slip between the two of them, slowly raised her arms and hooked the fly onto a small piece of leather adorning his breast plate.  “Perhaps this will bring you luck.”<br>
<br>
He could feel the flush returning to his cheeks at her nearness. Looking into her eyes then down at the beautiful token he said, “You are most welcome, Creapiing. I could not have done any differently, even if it had cost my own life.  I had to see you safe.”  He reached up to touch the soft fluff adorning the hook of the fly.  “Beauty that conceals a deadly blade.  I shall always think of you when I see it.” he said with a soft yet wolfish grin.<br>
<br>
A hidden smile crossed Creapiing's face at noticing the flush upon Khasirath's cheeks.  “This fly will help you to remember to use your hate and not your rage against Anari when we catch her.  Let us eat and rest so that she will feel your blade all the sooner.”<br>
<br>
He nodded thoughtfully as he watched her return to the fishing tackle, his mind returning to the hunt. <br>
<br>
~~~<br>
<br>
As the two Knights broke their camp they watched the terrain with keen violet eyes.  Suddenly they both paused, sensing something approaching.  Without a word they turned back-to-back, weapons ready as they looked for the source of their alarm.  Khasirath spotted it first - a flash of ebon black cutting through the biting wind and swirling snow, its wings beating powerfully as it neared its targets.  With a throaty cawing it stooped downwards as the Thresher raised his arm, and the bird landed easily on the proffered perch, flipping its wings back into place.  The raven's dark and familiar eyes darted from the Thresher to the Reaper and back as it let out a growling 'prr-uck!' of urgency.<br>
<br>
Creapiing stepped closer and swiftly removed the message tube from above the raven's talon.  The bird ruffled its feathers against the wind, darting its head from side to side as it watched the two Teir`Dal and the frozen plain around them.  Creapiing read the note and said, “Raveneye reports that Maladwen left Thurgadin and was teleported away.  Anari left the city alone a short time later, less than an hour ago.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded once, looking deeply into the raven's eyes.  “This is good news, indeed.  Thank you for your help.  Now return to your master.”<br>
<br>
He dropped his arm down a little then thrust it upwards in the same motion, casting the raven back to the winds.  The large bird circled them twice then soared off through the storm and the slowly brightening morn.<br>
<br>
Khasirath turned towards Creapiing, a feral grin on his thin lips.  “It seems that she is alone now.  Perhaps she thinks she can elude me this way, but it will not affect my tracking.  We will remain cautious of treachery; her friends are very resourceful when it comes to finding her.”<br>
<br>
Creapiing nodded, studying Khasirath's face.  “Indeed. I shall not let anything or anyone dishonor your duel.  But you must remember: Hate, not rage, must guide you.  Otherwise even in victory you shall be lost.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath frowned as he nodded, his hatred surging against his control as he sensed the nearness of his prey.  Swiftly he helped pack the last of the gear and turned a slow circle, gauging his path with inner sight.  When they'd set up camp they had been moving towards Thurgadin, but now he felt that Anari had doubled them back, headed towards the great bridge of ice and the harbor beyond.  With a growl he pulled a potion flask from his pouch.<br>
<br>
“Drink this my Reaper.  She has circled us and we shall need our best speed to keep her from reaching the Icebreaker.”<br>
<br>
Creapiing drank from the flask and handed it back.  Khasirath tossed back his draught of the wolf’s blood potion with a sneer, disliking the taste.  He stuffed the flask back into his pouch as they both shrouded themselves in shadow and loped off over the frozen ground.  The chill winds whipped them mercilessly, but Khasirath's hate burned so hot that he did not feel the cold.<br>
<br>
“Soon,” he thought, “Soon it shall be done.  This time I shall take her heart for Innoruuk as well as her soul.”<br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
Anari<br>
<br>
She had promised that she would stay.  Yet she broke that promise the second she stepped past the falls hiding the entrance to Thurgadin.  There was no way she was going to stay in one place when she knew it would only be a matter of time before the hunt for her began.  Securing her harpoon to her back, she cinched the Ravenscale cloak around her to keep out the chill, and headed out into the cold of Velious.  This is where S`Therik thought she was, she had to change that.  Kunark was as good a place as any for her to wait until she was ready to finish the game.  Besides, it was warm. <br>
<br>
She chuckled at the thought of him searching Velious only to have one of his spies tell him she was no longer there.  She would make him run from one end of the world to the other, letting his hate build with every step.  Growing with the knowledge that he must wait to avenge the indignity done to his sister, the assault against the pride of his House.  Sooner or later the strength it took to control the power of his hate would wane and that is when she would come for him.  When his rage blinds him he will fall to her as she fell to him.  Then, and only then, could he begin to know a fraction of the humiliation she had known at his hand.<br>
<br>
A psychotic smile formed on her lips at the thought of mounting his head above the mantle in the Shadowed Hall.<br>
<br>
She stopped.<br>
<br>
There were no more Shadows, at least not for her.  She had abandoned them.  Had given up everything she had ever held dear for her vengeance. <br>
<br>
She stood on the bridge that linked the Eastern Wastes to the Iceclad Ocean.  She had walked most of the way to the docks without even realizing she had done so.  “Bristlebane, what have you let me become?” <br>
<br>
Walking to the waist high ledge, she leaned her hand on the ice and stared out over the water at the rising sun.  So much had happened in the last - oh how many years?  Things had blurred together since she had first been rescued from S`Therik.  Her life had been one hunt after the other, trying to regain her strength and to become stronger.  He was always so much better than she; she had seen that while she watched him in the Arena.  The discipline he held over his own body was something she could only dream of attaining.  She had allowed the hate he had planted to grow and fester and control her, until it was the only emotion she truly felt.  Even her love was tainted.  How she adored Maladwen, but she saw now that her obsession with S`Therik was only going to lead to disaster. <br>
<br>
She sighed and looked down at the simple silver ring Maladwen had given her when they were married.   “How glad I am that you are not here, Mally.  The time has come to ends this, and I would not see you hurt for anything.”<br>
<br>
She closed her eyes, praying for the first time in many years.  Maladwen was going to be facing his greatest enemy, the source of his hate - perhaps at this very moment.  She prayed with all her heart and soul that if Bristlebane were to call one of them to Him, He would call her. <br>
<br>
With another sigh, she turned to head back to Thurgadin where she would await S`Therik.  But as she turned a dark shadow coalesced from the swirling snow, revealing the Knight as he stood a bare pace before her, his Indigo Saber’s point raised towards her throat, its sapphire pommel stone glowing balefully.  From within his ruddy helm his eyes glowed with his hate, the waves of it all but visible.  For the span of a single heartbeat, knowing the power of the man before her, she couldn’t help but wonder what life would have been like if she had made this one an ally instead of an enemy.  The heartbeat passed, and she sneered. <br>
<br>
His grin was feral as he watched her.  “You still pray to that fool Anari?  I thought I'd taught you the futility of that.  Indeed it seems you have forgotten many of my lessons.” <br>
<br>
“And I thought you would have come before now, S`Therik.  Ah well, the invitation I sent did not mention a place or time, now did it?” <br>
<br>
He growled as he spoke, “Is that what you call that cowardly attack on my sister?  An invitation?” <br>
<br>
“I needed something to capture your undivided attention.”  She leaned back against the ledge, folding her arms across her chest.  One hand, hidden beneath her other arm, slid into one of the many hidden pockets within the cloak.  “I believe it worked, don’t you?” <br>
<br>
A movement behind Khasirath caught her eye and she saw Creapiing, the Reaper of the Harvest.  She nodded toward the woman.  “Two against one, and here I thought you were an honorable bastard.” <br>
<br>
“You have no honor, and so you do not understand such things.  I will explain it simply, so that you might know.  This fight is for you and me alone.  The Reaper is here only to witness it, and to ensure that no one interferes. Should one of your friends try to stop me, or help you, they will die by her blade.  I hope it is clear to you now.”  He stepped back lowering the tip of his saber, and reached up with his shield hand to unclasp his traveling cloak, letting it pool like a shadow around his boots.<br>
<br>
“This ends now,” he growled deeply.<br>
<br>
She laughed at him, though inside she began to realize there was only one chance for her.  He would not show her mercy, would not spare her even if she swore herself to Innoruuk and all he believed.  He would kill her for what she did to Tzanntiel.  She had only one chance.  She had to win.  “I couldn’t agree with you more.” <br>
<br>
She jerked her arms away from her chest, throwing a handful of the dust from the pocket into his eyes while releasing her dirk from its hidden sheath.  He clawed at his eyes, trying to rid himself of the blinding powder. <br>
<br>
Catching the handle of his blade in her hand she ducked beneath his sword. As she passed beside him, she drove the dirk through the seam of his armor, piercing the flesh of his side.  Dropping into a roll she undid the clasp of her cloak and pulled the harpoon from her back. As she stood she unhooked the stiletto from her belt.  Her cloak fell around her feet, and she supported the shaft of the harpoon against her underarm. <br>
<br>
Khasirath spun to face her as his vision cleared, though his eyes were red from the powder.  He pulled the dirk from his side with a snarl. <br>
<br>
“A gift,” Anari taunted as she shifted her weight to the balls of her feet.  “I thought you would appreciate the blade that gutted your precious Tzanntiel.  A memento of how I got to your family, and a reminder that I can do it again!” <br>
<br>
His violet eyes blazed crimson as his hatred flared, “First blood dishonorably won, Rogue.  But this fight shall not end until you are dead.”  He lifted the slim blade to his lips, and licked his own blood from it as he let out a purring growl, his eyes pinning hers.  Almost carelessly he tossed the dirk aside so that it spun to land at Creapiing's feet. <br>
<br>
Her stiletto snapped in, the harpoon jabbing in the other way.  Anari repeated the routine, then a third time, each movement countered precisely by Khasirath’s own blade or shield.  Each strike was perfectly aimed, and each parry intercepted the attacking weapons perfectly.  Neither Anari nor Khasirath, locked through their staring eyes into mental combat, watched their hands through the physical movements.  Neither one blinked - not when the breeze of Khasirath’s high slice moved the hair atop the rouges head, not when Anari’s harpoon thrust came to a parried stop a hairsbreadth from Khasirath’s eye. <br>
<br>
The movements of their bodies began to catch the blur of hands and weapons.  Anari dipped a shoulder, stiletto lashing out straight ahead; Khasirath spun a complete circle, parrying behind his back as he flitted out of reach. <br>
<br>
A slight growl escaped S`Therik’s lips, his eyes flashing in the early dawn light. <br>
<br>
Anari laughed at him, stiletto and harpoon working furiously to keep his weapon at bay.  “Give in to the hate,” she teased.  “Let go of your discipline and let this be ended!” <br>
<br>
She didn’t understand… that was exactly the point. <br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
Khasirath <br>
<br>
Khasirath's hatred rose, burning through the air, driving the chill from his body. He spun and dodged, looking for the opportunity to strike, pressing Anari hard with furious blows of saber and shield. The stinging in his eyes and the taste of his own blood heightened his every sense, sharpening the lust for slaughter within him. <br>
<br>
Focused on the dance of death he held in his mind the image of Tzanntiel bleeding out her life in the street. <br>
<br>
Growling he slammed Anari back with his shield, driving her further back with a wide sweep of his saber. At the same time he began a hissing chant, drawing his power and hate into the incantation and releasing it upon Anari as she charged back into him. Her harpoon slid above the edge of his shield to pierce into his shoulder as the morning shadows congealed around her, slowing her step and constricting her legs painfully. Her surprised wince brought a wolfish grin to his thin lips. <br>
<br>
Pain did not exist for him. Nothing could distract him from the ginger-haired elf he fought. He kept her in front of him at all costs; he could not allow her the advantage of a strike at his back. With the Darkness engulfing her it was a simple matter. She could not rely on her agility as she normally would. <br>
<br>
Again and again they circled and clashed, each testing and pushing the other. She was fast, but her weapons were too light to easily breach his armour. He was more skilled, but it was hard to land blows upon her nimble form. Still their attacks found each other’s flesh often enough, and each strike that landed drove his frenzy higher. <br>
<br>
She backed away to try and circle him, and he took the opportunity to draw another spell, centering and focusing the hatred of his gift he hurled the enchantment upon her with a snarl. Almost instantly her face grew deeply flushed and she flinched in pain as her blood began to boil within her. <br>
<br>
She closed in fast, the fear of his magic apparent in her eyes. Her paired weapons rained in upon him, trying to keep him too distracted to cast again. The challenge of it was too delicious. Seeking the space between her strikes he all but whispered the short chant, rewarded at once by the reddish glow surrounding them both. He saw her arms tremble as her strength was sapped, and felt the power of it rush into his own body, driving the beginnings of fatigue from him. <br>
<br>
She darted back away to find a new angle, her breathing ragged. His eyes narrowed as he took her measure, delighting in the failings he sensed. <br>
<br>
“Ye are weak,” he hissed through his teeth. “I don’t think you’ve learned to hate at all.” <br>
<br>
Through her pain he saw her green eyes glitter as she bit back, “I’ll take that as a compliment!” <br>
<br>
A growl tore from his throat as he rushed her with ferocious attacks, driving her backwards across the bridge. <br>
<br>
Deftly she slipped to his flank, her harpoon whistling as it bit deeply into his ribs through the lighter chain under his arm. Twisting around to pull free of the barbed spear he hacked down across her arm with his saber, nearly breaking her grip on the shaft. <br>
<br>
She cried out from the pain, trying to retreat again. This time he didn’t allow her the luxury, pressing close despite the aching of his ribs. <br>
<br>
“You will wish you had learned better, Ravensblade,” he growled as he parried a thrust of her harpoon, flicking his saber around it to strike back in a riposte. The sensation of the Imbued blade tearing through the mail across her stomach brought a sudden cruel laugh from him. <br>
<br>
&quot;The only thing I wish is that I had stayed to watch her die!&quot; she spat back, stabbing at his face with her stiletto. He jerked his head back, but the slim blade still caught him, carving a deep line across his jaw. <br>
<br>
Breaking away he went into another flurry of attacks with his saber, bashing her back with his shield when she tried to close in again. Their blades rang and hissed against each other, shattering the stillness of the morning. <br>
<br>
“But you failed, Anari! Tzanntiel yet lives. And you helped her grow even stronger,” he taunted as they battled. “You have enflamed divine hate in her heart!” <br>
<br>
Anari drove into him with desperate strength, her harpoon and stiletto a whirling blur of death before her. Khasirath slid back into a defensive posture, his body well behind his shield as he endured the assault. Deep within himself he sought the very depths of his hate, and the link through it to his God. <br>
<br>
An inhuman roar burst from him as he smashed his shield into Anari, knocking her back and off balance. His hands became wrapped in a writhing black aura as Innoruuk’s own power burst through him. He could feel the Father’s dark presence in his mind, guiding and controlling him as he thrust his hands into Anari’s chest. <br>
<br>
Innoruuk’s power crackled sickeningly as it was unleashed, throwing Anari back across the ice as her entire body writhed from the unbearable pain. Khasirath shuddered deeply from the sensation of his God using him as a living conduit for His power.<br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
Anari<br>
<br>
It took every ounce of strength Anari could summon to keep from losing consciousness. The pain lanced through every fiber of her being at Khasirath’s touch. Her legs threatened to buckle beneath her, yet she somehow managed to stay on her feet. Taking a staggering step back she looked at the dark Knight. She could see the rage within his eyes, the ferocity in which they shone, but he would not lose control. She had underestimated him and she was going to pay for that mistake with her life. <br>
<br>
But by the gods, she would make him bleed! <br>
<br>
With a sudden renewed vigor, she stepped closer toward the drow. She snapped her head to the side as he attempted to remove it with his sword. The tip of the saber cut deeply into her cheek, blood immediately oozing down her face. She darted under his shield arm, stabbing the back of his knee with her blade. Very little damage was done, his armor too thick for her stiletto to penetrate well. Before she could turn he slammed his shield back, knocking the wind from her lungs and sending her stumbling forward against the ledge of the bridge. Her stiletto skittered from her hand and over the edge. Gasping to regain her breath she heard Khasirath chanting in a dark, low voice. As she spun to face him she could see the arcane glow around his hands rushing towards her, and she gasped as pain pulled at her heart. She could almost see the glow of her life force flying back into Khasirath, that feral grin of his widening as he drew it in with a sharp breath. <br>
<br>
Grasping her harpoon in both hands, she brought the shaft of the weapon up to block against his relentless charge. She was on the defensive, her back pressed against the edge of the bridge. Every muscle of her body screamed as she somehow managed to block attack after attack. She had only one route to go. <br>
<br>
Leaping onto the ledge of the bridge she narrowly avoided another swing of his sword. Precariously standing on the icy ledge she spun her harpoon around, its jagged tip pushing away a jab of his blade. <br>
<br>
And then she saw it - a trickle of dark blood from his lips. Her sudden confusion left her open. His saber took the chance, cleaving through the wooden staff of her harpoon. Realization struck her the same instant his blade drove into her thigh. Dropping her useless weapon she grabbed his arms, pulling him closer. <br>
<br>
&quot;Can you feel it?&quot; she hissed with a devilish chuckle. &quot;Can you feel yourself dying?&quot; <br>
<br>
Khasirath took a step back, jerking the blade from her leg. His eyes narrowed in defiance and confusion. She cried out in pain as the sudden flow of blood spurted from the wound in the rhythm of her racing heart. She fell to her knee, placing a hand over the gash. The white ice of the ledge became slippery from her blood. <br>
<br>
She watched him wipe his own blood from his lips. &quot;The poison on the blade would have weakened your muscles and slowed your attacks if you had let it work through your blood stream. But you licked the blade! Ingested, even I don’t know how painfully you will die.&quot; <br>
<br>
Khasirath took another uncertain step back, his eyes flicking towards Creapiing for a brief second. Anari heard the creaking of the leather wrapped around the hilt of his saber as his fist tightened reflexively. She actually had him off-guard. In his inscrutable violet eyes something unpleasant writhed, something that seemed to disturb him greatly. Was it fear? <br>
<br>
&quot;No,&quot; he growled, shaking his head. <br>
<br>
She reached into her boot and pulled out her last dagger, its hilt slick with her blood. &quot;Perhaps after you’re dead, I will finish what I started with Tzanntiel. No, that was too easy. Maybe I’ll use some of the techniques I learned from you and Kvariya on the little cleric. Vhalshae I believe her name was-&quot; <br>
<br>
She had gone too far. <br>
<br>
What little control S`Therik had left over his hate was gone and with a bestial scream he closed the distance between them and drove his sword into her chest. The indigo blade shattered through her ribs, her vital organs, only to pierce through her back. <br>
<br>
Her dagger fell from her hand. <br>
<br>
Her weight shifted, her foot slipping on the icy ledge. Instinctively her hand reached out, grasping onto Khasirath’s wrist as she began to fall. For a moment she hung there, suspended dangerously over the edge of the bridge. <br>
<br>
Gravity won. <br>
<br>
She tumbled over the edge, dragging the Teir`Dal with her. <br>
<br>
The wind whistled in her ears, her fading vision focused on S`Therik’s face. She felt a sudden jarring as she broke through the ice, then the deep chill cascading over her. Her eyes closed and she welcomed the darkness.<br>
